evaluation.response:
Yes—post it and I’ll mark exactly what’s causing the spikes and how to fix it. To get you an answer fast before 9:30, please paste:

- What board (e.g., Arduino Uno/Nano), what sensor board (e.g., QTR-8A/QTR-8RC or TCRT5000 modules), and which pins they’re on.
- Power setup (shared battery for motors + logic? any caps?).
- The sensor read function, the control loop (PID), and where you set motor PWM.
- Any Serial.print debugging you’re doing.

Quick fixes you can drop in now (often fixes “spikes” without hardware changes)
- Replace single reads with median-of-3 and a small exponential filter.
- Compute line position with a weighted average (centroid) using 32-bit math to avoid overflow.
- Don’t print every loop; print at 20–50 Hz max, or it will jitter timing.
- If using thresholds, add hysteresis (high and low thresholds).

Drop-in snippet for analog sensors (TCRT/“A” type). Paste these pieces in:

// Median-of-3 helper
int median3(int a,int b,int c){ if(a>b){int t=a;a=b;b=t;} if(b>c){int t=b;b=c;c=t;} if(a>b){int t=a;a=b;b=t;} return b; }

// Globals
const int N = 6;              // number of sensors
const int pins[N] = {A0,A1,A2,A3,A4,A5};
int minV[N], maxV[N];
int ema[N];                   // filtered readings 0..1000
bool calibrated = false;

// Call this once: show white, then black, or drive a quick lap and keep updating
void calibrateStep() {
  for (int i=0;i<N;i++){
    int r1=analogRead(pins[i]);
    int r2=analogRead(pins[i]);
    int r3=analogRead(pins[i]);
    int raw = median3(r1,r2,r3);
    if (!calibrated){ minV[i]=raw; maxV[i]=raw; }
    if (raw<minV[i]) minV[i]=raw;
    if (raw>maxV[i]) maxV[i]=raw;
  }
  calibrated = true;
}

int normRead(int i) { // returns 0..1000
  int r1=analogRead(pins[i]);
  int r2=analogRead(pins[i]);
  int r3=analogRead(pins[i]);
  int raw = median3(r1,r2,r3);
  int mn = minV[i], mx = maxV[i];
  if (mx<=mn) return 0;
  long v = (long)(raw - mn) * 1000L / (mx - mn);
  if (v<0) v=0; if (v>1000) v=1000;
  // EMA filter alpha ~ 0.3
  ema[i] = ema[i] + (int)(0.3f * (v - ema[i]));
  return ema[i];
}

int linePosition() { // centroid 0..(N-1)*1000
  long sumW = 0, sumWP = 0;
  for (int i=0;i<N;i++){
    int w = normRead(i);         // 0..1000
    sumW  += w;
    sumWP += (long)w * (i*1000);
  }
  static int last = (N-1)*500;   // center default
  if (sumW < 5) return last;     // line lost
  last = (int)(sumWP / sumW);
  return last;
}

// In loop:
// 1) call calibrateStep() for a bit at startup or when a button held
// 2) pos = linePosition();
// 3) error = target - pos; target = (N-1)*500;
// 4) feed error to your PID, then set motor PWM
// 5) only Serial.print every 20–50 ms, not every loop

If you use a Pololu QTR array, it’s even simpler: install the QTRSensors library and use qtr.calibrate() and qtr.readLineBlack() to get the line position directly (already normalized and filtered).

Common code mistakes I’ll look for
- Using digitalRead on analog sensors or using RC sensors without timing the discharge properly.
- Integer overflow in weighted sums (use long for sums/products).
- Blocking Serial.print in the fast loop (causes jitter that looks like spikes).
- No calibration per sensor (each diode is different).
- Hard thresholds with no hysteresis.
- Sampling once per loop at random timing relative to PWM; a tiny median/EMA fixes this quickly.

Paste your code and I’ll mark the exact lines to change. If you’re racing the clock, start by pasting just the sensor read + control loop first and I’ll respond fast.
